[src:fred-hill-coach/1976-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The Saint John's Johnnies won their first Division III championship, defeating the Towson State Tigers by a final score of 31−28.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1976-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The **1976 NCAA Division III Football Championship** playoffs were the fourth annual single-elimination tournament to determine the national champion of men's NCAA Division III college football.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1976-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The championship game was held at Garrett-Harrison Stadium in Phenix City, Alabama for the fourth consecutive year.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1976-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] Like the previous championship, eight teams competed in this edition.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1976-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] This list includes all head coaching changes announced during or after the season.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1977-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The Widener Pioneers won their first Division III championship, defeating the Wabash Little Giants by a final score of 39−36.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1977-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The **1977 NCAA Division III Football Championship** playoffs were the fifth annual single-elimination tournament to determine the national champion of men's NCAA Division III college football.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1977-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The championship game was held at Garrett-Harrison Stadium in Phenix City, Alabama for the fifth consecutive year.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1977-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] Like the previous two championships, eight teams competed in this edition.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1978-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The Baldwin–Wallace Yellow Jackets won their first Division III championship, defeating the Wittenberg Tigers by a score of 24−10.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1978-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The **1978 NCAA Division III Football Championship** playoffs were the sixth annual single-elimination tournament to determine the national champion of men's NCAA Division III college football.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1978-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The championship game was held at Garrett-Harrison Stadium in Phenix City, Alabama for the sixth consecutive year.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1978-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] Like the previous three championships, eight teams competed in this edition.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1979-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The Ithaca Bombers won their first Division III championship, defeating the Wittenberg Tigers by a final score of 14−10 in a re-match of the 1975 championship (won by Wittenberg).
[src:fred-hill-coach/1979-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The **1979 NCAA Division III Football Championship** playoffs were the seventh annual single-elimination tournament to determine the national champion of men's NCAA Division III college football.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1979-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The championship game was held at Garrett-Harrison Stadium in Phenix City, Alabama for the seventh consecutive year.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1979-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] Like the previous four championships, eight teams competed in this edition.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1980-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The Dayton Flyers won their first Division III championship, defeating the defending national champion Ithaca Bombers by a final score of 63−0.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1980-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The **1980 NCAA Division III Football Championship** playoffs were the eighth annual single-elimination tournament to determine the national champion of men's NCAA Division III college football.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1980-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The championship game was held at Garrett-Harrison Stadium in Phenix City, Alabama for the eighth consecutive year.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1980-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] Like the previous five championships, eight teams competed in this edition.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1981-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The Widener Pioneers won their second Division III championship, defeating the defending national champion Dayton by a final score of 17−10.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1981-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The **1981 NCAA Division III Football Championship** playoffs were the ninth annual single-elimination tournament to determine the national champion of men's NCAA Division III college football.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1981-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The championship game was held at Garrett-Harrison Stadium in Phenix City, Alabama for the ninth consecutive year.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1981-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] Like the previous six championships, eight teams competed in this edition.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1982-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The West Georgia Wolves won their first Division III championship, defeating the Augustana (IL) Vikings by a final score of 14−0.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1982-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The **1982 NCAA Division III Football Championship** playoffs were the tenth annual single-elimination tournament to determine the national champion of men's NCAA Division III college football.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1982-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] The championship **Stagg Bowl** game was held at Garrett-Harrison Stadium in Phenix City, Alabama for the tenth consecutive year.
[src:fred-hill-coach/1982-ncaa-division-iii-football-season] Like the previous seven championships, eight teams competed in this edition.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] In seven seasons as football head coach he compiled a record of 52–16–4, including four New Jersey State Athletic Conference titles.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] He also led them to the school's first 10-win season in 1981.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] As the Red Hawks' baseball coach, Hill went 148–91–1 in seven seasons.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] For his highly successful coaching efforts he was inducted into the Montclair State University Hall of Fame.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] His jersey number was also just the third to ever be retired at MSU, joining Sam Mills and Carol Blazejowski.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] Hill served as the Rutgers Scarlet Knights head baseball coach, a position that he held since from the 1984 through 2013 seasons.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] He recorded a record of 941–658–7 at Rutgers alone and sent 72 different players in 30 years to professional baseball careers.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] When Hill announced his retirement prior to the start of the 2014 NCAA baseball season, his 1,089 career wins ranked him 11th in college baseball history.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] He was named the A-10 Coach of the Year three times and Big East Coach of the Year once.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] Hill was hired as an assistant coach of the Caldwell University Cougars baseball program in 2015, a position he stayed in for two seasons.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] In 2017, Hill joined Kean University's baseball staff as an assistant coach.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] Hill's son, Fred Hill, was the Scarlet Knights men's basketball head coach.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] His brother is Brian Hill, a former assistant coach with the NBA's Detroit Pistons.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] He resided in Verona with his wife Evelyn of more than 50 years.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] He had 6 children (Nancy, Linda, Tracey, Karen, Jimmy and, Fred); Hill also had 12 grandchildren (Jessica, Danielle, Steven, Brian, James, Natalie, Andrew, Caroline, Nicholas, Alexandra, Giselle, and Giancarlo).
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] Fred Hill, Sr. attended Clifford Scott High School in East Orange, NJ.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] He also attended Upsala College and graduated in 1957.
[src:fred-hill-coach/fred-hill-coach] Fred Hill, Jr. attended Verona High School.
